social_posts.post_text: Ghonner - Graphite on Mulberry Paper - I had a dream in the late 90s where this creature showed me a portal in my house that connected to another dimension. Years later I made a painting called “The Doorknob of the Universe”. I later realized that I was trying to find a way to make my art all the time. Quit my day job. This shape is all about transformation. Death & rebirth. Change can be scary, especially if it’s healthy change. Letting go. Moving on. Ghonner, as in dead and gone, but of course much more than that. It seems happy.  #ghonner #alphabeast #graphitememory #graphitedrawing #drawing #draw #graphite #sketch #quickdraw #timbiskup #faceguts #art #hanglooseonagoose

LEAN
Currently @dale_zine #lean #miami #zine

Thank you @friezeofficial @monicalaurasimone

Tim Biskup’s background in the animation industry is palpable in the colours, swoops and bug-eyed monsters that populate his work. The Southern Californian artist’s illustrations and sculptures are wholesome, playful and a little bit punk. @dale_zine (pronounced dalé), a beloved local independent printer and publisher, opened their new location in January. Husband and wife co-founders Lillian Banderas (@lillianmarie) and Steve Saiz (@stevezyy) have become equal parts curators, publishers and hosts, with an upcoming exhibition programme at NADA that includes Autumn Casey, Germán Enrique, Natalia Chavarria and Alejandra Moros. Longtime fans, Banderas and Saiz display Biskup’s new graphite drawings of plush, totemic figures – ‘They’re minimal and beautiful to watch come alive,’ says Saiz. Many of these new pieces are pareidolic; in Lean 23, a cartoonish face emerges from tubular swirls and arcs, depending on how carefully you examine its contours. His process is mesmerizing – look up the artist’s TikTok page and you’ll marvel at his balletic wielding of a single hunk of graphite across the page. Visitors can also pick up an accompanying zine or custom prints and originals from the artist’s Los Angeles-based art space, @face.guts, and peruse Dale’s hefty selection of books, zines and prints by local artists and friends.

social_posts.post_text: Deeper in the process. For the first 15 years or so I almost never worked from sketches. I just let loose and something always happened. I’ve been making sketches all along but somehow they stayed apart. Feels good to have a plan sometimes. Might even be more relaxing because I’m just recreating something and I don’t have to think about what it is. Just form. #graphite #graphitedrawing #skull #timbiskup

4136 Verdugo Rd

Seeing how computers process ideas has changed me. Cold, raw, ferocious digging into what all of it amounts to looks like the debris floating around in my brain. An uncollected population of hybrids so foreign that they didn’t fit into my knowingly fluid aesthetic. Once you see it you can’t unsee it. Like toppling blocks of preconceived thought. So much like how I’ve always worked but now supercharged by heartless counterparts that spare no feelings. Enter chaos. Exit new. Here are my results. Enjoy or whatever.

Tim Biskup
Spring Collection 2023
Opening Friday, March 31st, 5-8pm at Face Guts 4136 Verdugo Rd, LA.

In what has become a yearly tradition, Tim Biskup will celebrate the coming of spring with a collection of recent work. New prints, including a stone lithograph made on a recent trip to Oaxaca, Mexico, a new serigraph printed in Paris, a series of large scale graphite drawings a few watercolor paintings and more. Utilizing Face Guts as a venue to showcase his work in all of its many formats has made for an expansive practice, fitting of an artist who never stops creating.

Note: The two new prints will only be available in-person at the opening this Friday. Any remaining prints will be made available online (via timbiskup.com) starting Monday, April 3rd at Noon (pacific time)

Ric Heitzman  @heitzmanric (1953-) lives and works in Los Angeles, CA.

Born in Dallas, Texas, Heitzman’s DIY spirit led him to create his own artistic path. While studying applied arts at Texas A&M, his radio show “APEWEEK” (with Gary Panter & Jay Cotton) expanded into live music, puppetry and street theater, catching the attention of a mysterious Hollywood impresario (Tex Henson) who hired the artist for an animation project. Ric thrived on the work and headed to the School of Art Institute of Chicago where he received his masters in filmmaking and eventually landed in New York City making graphics at ABC News. He was soon tapped by his old friend Gary Panter to develop a new TV show for kids called “Pee-Wee’s Playhouse”.  Heitzman co-designed, produced animation and provided voices for the shows' five seasons, earning 4 of the shows' 15 Emmy awards along the way. Following the success of Pee-Wee,  Ric took on a flurry of film & tv projects and teaching gigs while maintaining an artistic practice that has kept his art on the walls of galleries & museums dating back to 1975 in Texas and  including a solo show at La Luz De Jesus in 1989. In recent years art making has become his main focus. His recent book of ballpoint pen drawings celebrates a practice honed over decades and ready for fresh eyeballs.

This Friday 6-9pm at @face.guts is the opening of Cyclops
.
.
I’ve put this poor phallic symbol through hell. When he first showed up in the late 90s he was cute. Inspired by another cyclops hiding in the forest in Japan, scaring fishermen. I made him simple. A foolish man. He became perverse. Then violent. Then political. I used to say that he’s the monster we become when we think we know everything. I was battling inside. Channeling myopic rage. Under the rage was sadness. Under the sadness was peace. Now he is a conduit. Emoting and revealing. Well-rounded. Still a bit of a fool. I call him Helper.
.
New Paintings, Drawings, Merch and a display of archival materials. All sales are in-person only until after the opening. Early next week sometime.

The right hand draws and the left hand turns the paper. I didn’t realize I was doing this until @xavierburt took a video and I saw it. Seems impossible, but I was so focused on the technique happening on the right that the other side just did it’s thing without permission. This work is intuitive channeling. #automaticdrawing #graphitememory I’m feeling very grateful that I’ve had the time and space to follow this strange path. Thank you for lending me your eyeballs and support. Xo

I think that artists are inherently sensitive. The world tells us to become desensitized in order to fit in and to make sense out of the world in the same way that everybody else does. I think that for my experience as an artist to blossom I needed to be counter-intuitive and go towards my sensitivity to let it guide me. 

For me, that means that I cry a lot. I smile a lot. I have intense feelings all day long. I turn those feelings into art so that everyone can feel them. Thank you for watching!

TIM BISKUP // SMOKE IS A NEW BODY OF WORKS BY STORIED LOS ANGELES ARTIST TIM BISKUP. KNOWN FOR HIS UNIQUELY FLUID GRAPHITE ON PAPER DRAWING PRACTICE, TIM BISKUP // SMOKE REPRESENTS THE RESULTS OF THE ARTIST’S VAST EXPERIMENTATION OF TECHNIQUES TO TRANSITION THE INITIAL EFFORTLESSNESS OF EXPRESSION TO THE PERMANANCE OF CANVAS
.
.
Drawing is meditation. My attention is on what is emerging. Like watching life form. I don’t know what it’s going to be. My goal is to avoid attaching to what my mind is trying to get me to do. The materials are basic, so I don’t feel much restraint to the flow. What emerges is deeply personal and therapeutic.
.
The technique of transitioning these drawings onto canvas took years to develop... but is now an equal (but different) form of meditation. It’s about taking care of the image. Guiding it onto the wall with its integrity intact. The paintings are like monuments to the specific temporal moments when the drawings happened.
— TB
.

RunComeTest - Graphite on Kraft Paper - Yesterday I pulled out a stack of paper I was planning to throw out and decided to do some drawings on them. Just seeing how it feels to draw on something that I consider to be truly worthless. It proved my theory that low consequences make me feel more relaxed and open. I’ll post a few in the next few days. Feels like a tiny breakthrough. More relaxed is important these days. Hope you enjoy! Thank you for watching.
